This paper discusses the design of a distributed social network that addresses user privacy, security, and service availability. The focus on distributed architecture and resiliency suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The discussion of threat and trust models, as well as the use of P2P networks, suggests that the paper may also belong to the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) and Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories. The emphasis on user privacy and security also suggests that the paper may belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Finally, the use of distributed frameworks and the examination of prior work in P2P networks suggests that the paper may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category.
